article.description:
Chris Paul had 24 points, 12 assists and 12
rebounds for his first career triple-double and the 
Hornets beat the Raptors 120-113 in double overtime Sunday
night.
article.headline: Paul's first triple-double lifts Hornets in 2OT
article.linkText: Paul's first triple-double lifts Hornets in 2OT
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- The New Orleans Hornets needed every point, assist and rebound of Chris Paul's first career triple double to get past the Toronto Raptors. Paul had 24 points, 12 assists and 12 rebounds and the Hornets beat the Raptors 120-113 in double overtime Sunday night. Paul grabbed his 10th rebound in the fourth quarter to complete the triple-double. "This is huge for our confidence. We're in a tough situation right now where we are trying to fight for the eighth spot in the playoffs," Paul said. "We knew we had Detroit coming up so we really needed this one." The rookie added seven points in the second overtime, including a key 3-pointer that gave New Orleans a 111-103 lead with 3 minutes left. David West added 23 points for the Hornets, who have won three straight after losing 12 of 13. New Orleans began the day two games behind Sacramento for the eighth and final playoff berth in the Western Conference. The Kings beat the Clippers later on Sunday night. "He's just a great little player. He's got a lot of heart," Hornets coach Byron Scott said of Paul. "We knew the triple double would come sooner than later, but obviously tonight we really needed it. I thought he really came through big time." The game featured a matchup of two of the best rookies in the NBA. Charlie Villanueva had 25 points and a career-high 18 rebounds for Toronto. Morris Peterson had 27 points and Joey Graham added a career-high 19 points for the Raptors, who have lost four straight. Mike James went 5-for-25 from the field. "Sometimes me and the rim just don't agree," James said. "For 20 of the shots tonight me and the rim weren't really on good terms. I think I did something to her last night. I normally treat her good, talk to her nice. I don't ever curse her out, but tonight maybe she was a little mad at me, but that's all right. I'm going to give her flowers and candy before the next game." James had 15 points and 10 assists. Rasual Butler got New Orleans going in the second overtime with a 3-pointer as New Orleans began the extra period on 11-3 run. The Hornets outscored Toronto 20-13 in the second overtime. Peterson missed a potential winning jumper at the buzzer at the end of the first overtime. New Orleans led by as many as 18 points in the second half, but Toronto closed the gap in the fourth quarter -- outscoring the Hornets 23-15. With Toronto down 10, James sparked a 12-0 run with a 3-pointer with 4:43 left. New Orleans scored 2 points in the final five minutes of regulation. Graham's two free throws gave Toronto an 85-83 lead with 2:01 left -- its first lead since the first quarter. But Mark Jackson made an open jumper to tie it with 25 seconds left and James missed a layup in traffic at the buzzer.

Game notes
Toronto's Darrick Martin said he and Matt Bonner will try to go to Indianapolis for the NCAA championship game Monday night between UCLA and Florida. Martin went UCLA and Bonner went to Florida. ... The Hornets ended a five-game losing streak to Toronto.
